<DOC><DOCNO> AP880902-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0745EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     09-02 0258</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Boat People,0268</SECOND><HEAD>Hong Kong Planning New Shelter For Boat People</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government said today it will build a newemergency shelter for the growing number of Vietnamese refugeesarriving by boat to this British colony.   The center, which is to open by the end of September, will bethe sixth center built to house Vietnamese boat people who landedafter mid-June. Hong Kong announced a new policy that classifiedmost of the boat people who arrived after June 15 as illegalimmigrants subject to repatriation.   Vietnamese who arrived earlier are considered political refugeeseligible for resettlement.   More than 9,000 new refugees _ including 2,375 in August _arrived since the measure took effect, although it was designed tostop the rising influx of boat people. The number of Vietnamese inHong Kong refugee camps totals 25,000, according to governmentstatistics.   The new center is expected to shelter about 3,000 people inhuts, the government said.   Some residents near the site of the future shelter said theywill oppose it unless authorities guarantee local services will notbe disrupted, government-run radio reported.   Hanoi said it will examine on a case-by-case basis theVietnamese who arrived in Hong Kong after mid-June, if theyvolunteer to return to their homeland, 500 miles southwest of HongKong.   However, only 1 percent of the boat people have requestedrepatriation to their communist homeland, and none has returned sofar, a government spokeswoman said today.   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees is processingtheir applications to return.</TEXT></DOC>